</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="33BFC5B557A65C80AE14F2544DC3AF7A" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" type="description">
<paragraph id="E9D4930DDB25FA572E212A7B8AA34777" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Microscopic description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2B03284EA9072385721913FB2279F976" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">
Spores amygdaloid or limoniform, very strongly papillate, on ave. 14-16 
<normalizedToken id="8EB9CF7C45D0FC5BE777E2BC18A857C6" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
8.5-9.5 
<normalizedToken id="C57B6BABE0842E5707ACAA0BDDBED9DE" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
, ave. Q = 1.6-1.8, pale brown to yellow brown, weakly guttulate, almost smooth to weakly ornamented (O1O2), perispore not loosening (P0), distinctly to rather strongly dextrinoid (D2D3). Basidia 23-44 
<normalizedToken id="F586017C9777B4A776257E654DDAF899" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
6-10 
<normalizedToken id="3F081FE44639C5BBF9E2FFD705A56C2D" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
, ave. Q = 3.1-4.3, characteristically 2-spored. Cheilocystidia lageniform or ventricose, occasionally clavate-ventricose, characteristically geniculate and septate, on ave. 40-70 
<normalizedToken id="F261D26B2A051CB25FE9D19CB1179347" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
5.5-6.5 (apex) 
<normalizedToken id="CA52585AA0F143A575D0E15A72629754" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
4.5-5.5 (middle) 
<normalizedToken id="AFDD10DA9B702BAF66FAFB5BB343EA9E" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
8-10.5 (base) 
<normalizedToken id="B06A2768F179BE9BEB2552C0154060BB" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
, ratios A/M = 1.02-1.44, A/B = 0.53-0.75, B/M = 1.48-2.03. Epicutis an ixocutis, up to 130 
<normalizedToken id="9CDADD2AE4E9E9642736C9D69180E919" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
thick (measured from exsiccata), maximum hyphae width 6 
<normalizedToken id="1EA98512FAE999F49B5254237D2C62B8" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
, ixocutis hyphae sometimes encrusted, shape of trama elements beneath subcutis isodiametric. Caulocystidia similar to cheilocystidia, up to 120 
<normalizedToken id="EE4369D4FE724DC7FBB9C0C51383174D" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
long.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="CE2922450A74C06E4D4AC81402C7EAA6" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" type="collections examined">
<paragraph id="99A9DA6E938ED81F85077A2B2554325A" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Collections examined.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="48DF222D10860352EB34BF1E3E1D0000" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis id="D4835FD34D0F01C7F04143F4832AA0FD" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">N-Greenland</emphasis>
: Zackenberg, 
<normalizedToken id="3C21DE1D6E3E1A595BF4993E5B2C2B6E" originalValue="Sydkæret">Sydkaeret</normalizedToken>
, 
<geoCoordinate id="D1D53EA715E4D33F1ACDDF487895764F" degrees="74.50" direction="north" orientation="latitude" precision="555" value="74.5">74.50°N</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate id="7E139D878AFAFE6089F96D24B296A303" degrees="20.75" direction="west" orientation="longitude" precision="555" value="-20.75">20.75°W</geoCoordinate>
, 19 Aug 1999, T. Borgen (TB99.376, C-F-104295), 30 m, with 
<taxonomicName id="2AB0D12916DD278F471F6584D3EE5F70" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Salicaceae" genus="Salix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Salix arctica" order="Salicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="arctica">
<emphasis id="8802BD90905815A32075E260F0D1EE27" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Salix arctica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<emphasis id="63BC404B1D664C9E00087494E1752D85" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">E-Greenland</emphasis>
: Jameson Land, Nerlerit Inaat/Constable Pynt, west side of Nathorst Fjeld, 
<geoCoordinate id="44B8735843F5CEC11A68B9DE9B49E358" degrees="70.76" direction="north" orientation="latitude" precision="555" value="70.76">70.76°N</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate id="B6A069C383CC1B7EFC6A86B552D1DE22" degrees="22.64" direction="west" orientation="longitude" precision="555" value="-22.64">22.64°W</geoCoordinate>
, 5 Aug 2017, H. Knudsen (HK17.101, C-F-104997), 40 m, with 
<taxonomicName id="FF2BA00DA260B5D004B8C3AF02D4BEF2" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Salicaceae" genus="Salix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Salix" order="Salicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="4A1221D7512BC25DB57299A92AD005A7" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Salix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. in tundra.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="1446EEDF530FAE523BFC14AB07D9E626" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="D4C0584DECCEC5F35DD6A0C94269E348" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="530755663C90D85F214556B3BCE50627" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Recently described from the southern Carpathians in Romania from a single collection. The two Greenland collections are the first recorded since the type has been published. Both are from the High Arctic zone in Greenland at 70° and 74°N, and it is thus in the northernmost group among the 28 Greenland species. The records are the first from North America and the first outside Europe.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="41ACEDDB5A627BD65968CCBA794DAB89" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" type="habitat">
<paragraph id="FB8A27F84CF5FAAD404B42F9C1DE05BF" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Habitat and ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B242944A2B41BC599787EDF40E3963F6" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">
Only two records, both most likely with 
<taxonomicName id="8F5C91252B1BD90C030CD1A6F3FCBEA0" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Salicaceae" genus="Salix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Salix arctica" order="Salicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="arctica">
<emphasis id="C14DD914F7F360545A0EF4222710179D" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Salix arctica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and both on calcareous soil. The only previous collection, the type, grew with 
<taxonomicName id="1065E1A5BE50C77F6BCA327311AD553A" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Salicaceae" genus="S." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. retusa" order="Salicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="retusa">
<emphasis id="65F674F69976E3670E0D267AA2F99EF7" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">S. retusa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
L. at 2270 m a.s.l. in the Carpathians (
<bibRefCitation id="D30894D247D170480C9E480B298F5B9D" DOI="https://doi.org/10.3852/15-097" author="Eberhardt, U" journalOrPublisher="Mycologia" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" pagination="1285 - 1303" refId="B11" refString="Eberhardt, U, Ronikier, A, Schuetz, N, Beker, HJ, 2015a. The genus Hebeloma in the alpine belt of the Carpathians including two new species. Mycologia 107: 1285 - 1303, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3852/15-097" title="The genus Hebeloma in the alpine belt of the Carpathians including two new species." url="https://doi.org/10.3852/15-097" volume="107" year="2015 a">Eberhardt et al. 2015a</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation id="B85CDCBC3756DE1195990058F94CFE60" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1134/S1995425518050086" author="Shiryaev, AG" journalOrPublisher="Contemporary Problems of Ecology" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" pagination="458 - 471" refId="B44" refString="Shiryaev, AG, Zmitrovich, IV, Ezhov, ON, 2018. Taxonomic and ecological structure of basidial macromycetes biota in polar deserts of the northern hemisphere. Contemporary Problems of Ecology 11: 458 - 471, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1134/S1995425518050086" title="Taxonomic and ecological structure of basidial macromycetes biota in polar deserts of the northern hemisphere." url="https://doi.org/10.1134/S1995425518050086" volume="11" year="2018">Shiryaev et al. (2018)</bibRefCitation>
reported from 
<bibRefCitation id="3C2B99F1AEF5C8C0B54A97D955F3AADF" author="Zmitrovich, IV" editor="Matveeva, NV" journalOrPublisher="Marafon, St. Petersburg" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" pagination="211 - 225" refId="B54" refString="Zmitrovich, IV, Ezhov, ON, 2015. Agaricoid fungi (Basidiomycota, Agaricomycetes). In: Matveeva, NV, Ed., Rasteniya i griby polyarnykh pustyn' severnogo polushariya (The Plants andFungi of Polar Deserts of Northern Hemisphere). Marafon, St. Petersburg: 211 - 225" title="Agaricoid fungi (Basidiomycota, Agaricomycetes)." volumeTitle="Rasteniya i griby polyarnykh pustyn' severnogo polushariya (The Plants andFungi of Polar Deserts of Northern Hemisphere)." year="2015">Zmitrovich and Ezhov (2015)</bibRefCitation>
the presence of 
<taxonomicName id="18555FF24E1492CB1767DC3564C1FD89" authorityName="Groger &amp; Zschieschang" authorityYear="1981" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Hymenogastraceae" genus="Hebeloma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Hebeloma gigaspermum" order="Ostropales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="gigaspermum">
<emphasis id="EBE8E95DBF165453B26100EF75884768" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Hebeloma gigaspermum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<normalizedToken id="4C6EA890D0B58B97A64A85C5B85CB87D" originalValue="Gröger">Groeger</normalizedToken>
&amp; Zschiesch. from Franz Josefs Land (Russia). According to 
<bibRefCitation id="04782AC41FA9B3D322F51FEF13BA899D" author="Beker, HJ" journalOrPublisher="Fungi Europaei Edizioni Tecnografica, Lomazzo" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" refId="B4" refString="Beker, HJ, Eberhardt, U, Vesterholt, J, 2016. Hebeloma (Fr.) P. Kumm. Fungi Europaei Edizioni Tecnografica, Lomazzo" title="Hebeloma (Fr.) P. Kumm." year="2016">Beker et al. (2016)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<taxonomicName id="2F24F2F5E645EE103DBB387763DB127A" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Salicaceae" genus="H." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="H. gigaspermum" order="Salicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="gigaspermum">
<emphasis id="D44027BA8F3EB50EFD380DA48A2E2F13" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">H. gigaspermum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is most likely a synonym of 
<taxonomicName id="66E6E030ED63767481D3FCC1744D61A3" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Salicaceae" genus="H." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="H. nauseosum" order="Salicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="nauseosum">
<emphasis id="CD7C2B452ACA5DA7CDEED18476D94BB5" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">H. nauseosum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Sacc. Since neither 
<taxonomicName id="60794AE5176474B6E7C9C8398A9564D6" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Salicaceae" genus="H." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="H. nauseosum" order="Salicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="nauseosum">
<emphasis id="95D32FFED246CACAA7522FC08BD843DC" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">H. nauseosum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
nor any other species of 
<taxonomicName id="B5E26F3A4FE16A779AFF303ACC082DAA" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Salicaceae" genus="H." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="H. subsp. sect." order="Salicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="section" section="Sacchariolentia" species="nauseosum" subSpecies="sect.">H. sect. Sacchariolentia</taxonomicName>
occurs in arctic areas, it may be that the large spores and the occurrence in the High Arctic zone rather point to 
<taxonomicName id="C3E50F8CD403C4D9C9007F11D2FBC5FB" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Salicaceae" genus="H." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="H. grandisporum" order="Salicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="grandisporum">
<emphasis id="E1E058D2BDFEAFA32D41ED04BAC102C8" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">H. grandisporum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="B75DAABEEFC8C45EECFA499F7B830B2C" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" type="notes">
<paragraph id="7E21B65AA54FAE94A18B62F1EB7555C1" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FBE127D91DEBC34CE00173A5EE13A95D" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">
<taxonomicName id="84055DAE8AC29903A47ECF2DB2AD74E3" authorityName="Beker, U. Eberh. &amp; A. Ronikier; Eberhardt, Ronikier, Schuetz &amp; Beker, Mycologia 107 (6): 1293" authorityYear="2015" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Hymenogastraceae" genus="Hebeloma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Hebeloma grandisporum" order="Ostropales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="grandisporum">
<emphasis id="5891C669B472047B4649E12D7E3F5FE5" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Hebeloma grandisporum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is one of the most easily recognized among the arctic-alpine 
<taxonomicName id="9560E6A1515AD05EA37F2DB2A72B98D9" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Hymenogastraceae" genus="Hebeloma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Hebeloma" order="Ostropales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="C3AC3DCCF094B27D89C1528B062DD4ED" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Hebeloma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species by the small basidiomes, the large spores, the relatively few, distant lamellae and large, 2-spored basidia. To date, it is the only 
<taxonomicName id="EFDF77760592D5C204D8B2F464300942" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Hymenogastraceae" genus="Hebeloma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Hebeloma" order="Ostropales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="A8DCF94D47620A447C4D0E097FCBA376" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Hebeloma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, of which we are aware, that has consistently 2-spored basidia.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
